# REST API Design Standards

## Endpoint Conventions
- Use plural nouns: `/api/v1/users`, not `/api/v1/user`
- Use nested routes for relationships: `/api/v1/users/:id/orders`
- Maximum 2 levels of nesting — flatten beyond that
- All endpoints versioned: `/api/v1/...`

## Request/Response
- Validate all inputs with Zod schemas
- Return consistent response envelope:

```typescript
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T;
  meta?: { page: number; pageSize: number; total: number };
  errors?: ApiError[];
}
```

- Use proper HTTP status codes: 200 (OK), 201 (Created), 204 (No Content), 400 (Bad Request), 401 (Unauthorized), 403 (Forbidden), 404 (Not Found), 409 (Conflict), 422 (Validation Error), 500 (Internal)
- Never expose internal errors to clients — map to user-safe messages

## Security
- All endpoints require authentication unless explicitly marked public
- Use rate limiting on all public endpoints
- Sanitize all string inputs
- Never include sensitive data in URL query parameters (use POST body or headers)

<example>
// ✅ Correct: validated input, consistent response, proper status
const createUserSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email(),
  name: z.string().min(2).max(100),
  role: z.enum(['admin', 'user', 'viewer']),
});

app.post('/api/v1/users', async (req, res) => {
  const parsed = createUserSchema.safeParse(req.body);
  if (!parsed.success) {
    return res.status(422).json({ errors: formatZodErrors(parsed.error) });
  }
  const user = await userService.create(parsed.data);
  return res.status(201).json({ data: user });
});
</example>
